          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Key fact that changes the usual calculus: **DHI went free + Apache-2.0 on 2025-12-17.** The whole catalog — including Postgres 15–18 — is now the Community tier at $0, with zero-CVE, signed SBOM, and SLSA L3 provenance. So the \"DHI = expensive Docker subscription\" assumption is dead. The cost is now almost entirely engineering, not licensing.\n\n## DHI for Postgres — what it actually costs\n\n**Licensing: $0** (Community tier, `dhi.io/postgres:17-debian13`). Paid tiers (Select/Enterprise) only buy you SLA-backed 7-day CVE remediation, FIPS/STIG variants, and custom builds — none of which a self-hosted multi-tenant chat app needs at this stage. Confidence: high.\n\n**Engineering: a few hours, and entirely in your dev compose ergonomics.** Concrete friction against your current `compose.yaml`:\n\n- **Healthcheck breaks.** Your `test: [\"CMD-SHELL\", \"pg_isready ...\"]` needs `/bin/sh`; DHI runtime images are distroless (no shell). Fix: switch to exec form `[\"CMD\", \"pg_isready\", \"-U\", \"postgres\", \"-d\", \"llame\"]`. The `pg_isready` binary ships with the image, so this is trivial. Confidence: high.\n- **Non-root volume ownership.** DHI runs as a non-root UID. Your `llame-pgdata` volume and the read-only `initdb` mount may need ownership/permission adjustment on first boot. This is the one real gotcha. Confidence: moderate — needs a test boot.\n- **`initdb.d` compatibility.** Your `01-app-role.sql` runs via `/docker-entrypoint-initdb.d`. DHI's Postgres preserves the standard entrypoint, so this should carry over — but verify, since this script provisions the non-superuser `app` role that your entire RLS moat depends on. Confidence: moderate.\n- **Lost `docker exec … sh` debugging.** No shell means `db:psql` / `db:logs`-style poking changes. You'd run `psql` as the entrypoint or keep a `-dev` variant for local use. Minor.\n- Possible `docker login dhi.io` step self-hosters must do, even on the free tier. Minor distribution friction.\n\n**Should you switch now? Qualified yes — but not for the dev DB.** Hardening a localhost dev database has ~zero security value; the win is supply-chain hygiene (signed provenance, SBOM, zero-CVE) on the **artifact you ship to self-hosters**. You don't have a production/deploy image yet — there's only this one dev `compose.yaml`. So \"switch now\" today literally means \"swap the dev image and slightly degrade dev ergonomics.\" Given it's free and the worktree is `docker-hardening`, do it as the baseline for the *deployable* compose, pinned **by digest**, and keep dev ergonomics intact. Don't trade `db:psql` convenience for theater on localhost.\n\n## pgbouncer — no, not now\n\nYou have no problem it solves. Current state: postgres.js with `max: 1`, single NestJS instance → one connection. pgbouncer exists to stop many clients/instances from exhausting Postgres `max_connections` (default 100). You're at 1.\n\nTwo things worth recording so future-you doesn't get burned when the durable run worker + multiple instances arrive (SPEC §9.5):\n\n- **Your RLS design is already pgbouncer-safe.** `TenantDbService.runAs` sets `app.current_user_id` transaction-locally, inside the txn — that's compatible with pgbouncer **transaction mode**, which is exactly the thing session-state-based tenancy usually breaks on. Good. Don't regress to session-level `SET`.\n- **One landmine for later:** postgres.js uses named prepared statements by default; transaction-mode pgbouncer breaks them. When you adopt it, set `prepare: false` in `db.ts`.\n\nThe more immediate smell isn't pgbouncer — it's `max: 1` in `apps/api/src/db/db.ts`. Under any real concurrency that serializes every request's DB work through a single connection per process. If it's a deliberate early-dev simplification for `runAs` correctness, fine — but flag it for revisit *before* you ever reach for pgbouncer. App-side pool sizing is the first lever; pgbouncer is the second, when you have N processes.\n\n## Prioritized plan\n\n1. **pgbouncer: defer.** Add a one-line note (AGENTS.md gotchas) capturing the two facts above. Zero work now, saves a debugging session later. Highest leverage / lowest cost.\n2. **Revisit `max: 1`** before it becomes a latency mystery. Decide: is it intentional? If not, size it properly.\n3. **DHI: adopt for the shipped image, by digest, free tier** — when you create the deploy artifact. If you want to land it now in this worktree: swap the image, convert the healthcheck to exec form, boot once to shake out the non-root volume + initdb issues, keep a shell-bearing variant for `db:psql`. Half a day, mostly verification.\n4. **Don't pay for DHI Select/Enterprise** until a compliance requirement (FIPS/STIG/SLA) actually lands on you. Self-hosted OSS doesn't generate that requirement on its own.\n\nNet: pgbouncer is premature; DHI is cheap (free) supply-chain hygiene best applied to the deployable image, not the dev convenience DB.\n\nSources:\n- [DHI Postgres catalog](https://hub.docker.com/hardened-images/catalog/dhi/postgres)\n- [Docker Hardened Images docs](https://docs.docker.com/dhi/)\n- [DHI pricing & alternatives (Minimus)](https://www.minimus.io/post/docker-hardened-images-alternatives)\n- [DHI 2026 architect's guide (MrCloudBook)](https://mrcloudbook.com/docker-hardened-images-the-2026-architects-guide-to-supply-chain-compliance/)",
