          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "The parity principle is right (12-factor dev/prod parity, and yes it's how the OpenClaw-style \"clone and run\" model works). But the argument you gave for it — \"we may not see a DB issue locally if we don't use the same env\" — points at the wrong layer, and that misdiagnosis will lead you to spend effort where parity doesn't pay and skip it where it does.\n\n## The parity that catches DB bugs is not the base image\n\nA DB issue that \"only shows in prod\" comes from, in rough order: Postgres **major/minor version**, `postgresql.conf` settings, missing/different **extensions**, **locale/collation**, a **connection pooler** sitting in the path, or auth/role config. It almost never comes from the container's distro layer. `postgres:17-alpine` and `dhi.io/postgres:17-debian13` run the *same Postgres engine* — same query planner, same RLS semantics, same wire protocol. So swapping to DHI buys you ~zero *behavioral* DB parity. Confidence: high.\n\nWhat DHI actually homogenizes is your **security/supply-chain surface** (same CVE posture, same non-root UID, same filesystem). That's a legitimate reason to want one image — just name it correctly. Don't justify DHI with \"catch DB bugs\"; justify it with \"same hardened artifact everywhere.\" The thing that actually catches DB bugs is pinning version + config + extensions, which you should do regardless of DHI.\n\n## Single-image makes the distroless tax permanent — commit to the debug story\n\nWhen DHI was \"the prod image only,\" distroless (no shell) was a prod-ops concern. Under dev=prod single-image, **every developer** loses `docker exec … sh`, and so does every self-hoster debugging their own instance. That's the real cost of your model, and it's permanent.\n\nYou have two honest resolutions, and one trap:\n- **Ephemeral debug container** — attach a shell-bearing container to the running namespace when needed. Keeps the image pure. This is the Chainguard/distroless-shop answer.\n- **`psql` as a documented path** — `docker exec` the `psql` binary directly (it ships in the image), no shell needed, covers 90% of `db:psql`.\n- **Trap:** a `-dev` profile override that swaps in a shell-bearing image. The moment you do that, you've reintroduced the dev/prod image delta you adopted single-image to avoid. If you go this route, be honest that your parity is \"same image in normal operation, different in debug\" — which is fine, but it's not the absolute you're framing it as.\n\n## Your own parity principle argues *for* pgbouncer earlier — which is why topology is the real decision\n\nThis is the part to sit with. If prod will run pgbouncer, then by your parity logic dev must run it too — because the pooler is *exactly* the subtle layer that produces \"only shows in prod\" bugs: transaction-mode pooling breaks postgres.js's default prepared statements, and it interacts with your transaction-local `app.current_user_id`. Running dev without the pooler while prod has it would be the single worst parity gap you could pick, given your RLS design.\n\nSo the question isn't \"should we add pgbouncer now\" — it's **\"will prod ever have a pooler?\"** and that's downstream of prod topology, which you haven't pinned:\n\n- **Single-node self-hosted** (one API process + one Postgres — the realistic llame MVP for a family/small team): you likely *never* need pgbouncer. A sane app-side pool is enough. Parity is satisfied with no pooler anywhere. **This is where I'd bet for v0.1.**\n- **Scale-out** (multiple API/worker instances, or serverless): pgbouncer belongs in the **base** compose so dev inherits it — not bolted on in a prod-only override.\n\nDecide topology first; pgbouncer falls out of it. Don't add it speculatively.\n\nOne caveat to the OpenClaw analogy: OpenClaw is file-first SQLite — embedded, no server, no pooler, no image. \"Clone and run\" parity is trivial for an embedded DB. You're running **server Postgres with a non-superuser RLS role model and a future worker**. The parity surface is genuinely heavier; the analogy undersells it.\n\n## `max: 1` is now a parity bug in waiting\n\nUnder dev=prod, your pool config must be the *same code path* in both. `max: 1` in `apps/api/src/db/db.ts` won't be your prod value, so today dev and prod would diverge on the exact dimension (pool sizing) most likely to mask concurrency/connection bugs locally. Make it env-driven with one realistic default shared by both. Confidence: high — this contradicts your stated goal more directly than the image choice does.\n\n## Revised plan, ranked by leverage\n\n1. **Pin prod topology** (single-node vs scale-out). It's the blocking decision; pgbouncer, pool sizing, and TLS all fall out of it. Cheap to decide, expensive to leave implicit.\n2. **Fix `max: 1` → env-driven, shared default.** This is your most direct current parity violation. Small, do it now.\n3. **Structure compose as base + overrides** (compose profiles / `compose.override.yaml`). Base = the homogeneous core (image, PG version, config). Overrides = port exposure (dev), TLS/backups/replicas (prod). This is what reconciles \"one image\" with \"different surfaces\" honestly — and it's where pgbouncer goes *if and when* topology demands it (in base, not prod-only).\n4. **DHI: yes, for the right reason** (free supply-chain hygiene, single hardened artifact), pinned by digest. Pre-commit to the distroless debug story (ephemeral container or `psql`-direct) before you swap, and convert the healthcheck to exec form. Don't sell it internally as DB-bug parity — it isn't.\n5. **pgbouncer: only after step 1 says scale-out.** When it lands, it lands in base compose with postgres.js `prepare: false`. Until then it's complexity for a problem you don't have.",
